\intbl \ql \b Summary of Evaluator Report\b0 \line It should be noted that the first evaluator recommended that the programme should not be accredited. The second evaluator\'27s report is more favourable recommending provisional accreditation. The second evaluator indicated that Criteria 1 and 2 are in need of improvement\'2C while Criteria 5\'2C 6 and 9 are judged to be commendable. \line The second evaluator stated that\'2C although the course offerings cover\'2C in sufficient academic depth\'2C the various areas of the discipline of International Relations\'2C the programme does not indicate a grounded bias in locating the discipline within the African continent. That is there are only two optional courses  that have a link to the continent \'28\'E2\'80\'9CPolitical Change in Africa\'E2\'80\'9D and \'E2\'80\'9CPolitical Economy of Southern Africa\'E2\'80\'9D\'29. Although the degree is not being offered in \'E2\'80\'9CAfrican International Relations\'E2\'80\'9D\'2C the evaluator felt it should align much more effectively with the institution\'27s mission by offering more Africa-focused courses. It is noted that one of the primary objectives of the programme is to \'E2\'80\'9CPrepare students for life as scholars in academic institutions and research environments in South Africa and across Africa\'E2\'80\'9D. \line The other issue that has not been clarified and raises concern is that the programme is offered at two sites\'2C that is\'2C in Pietermaritzburg \'28PMB\'29 and Howard College \'28HC\'29. This is in and of itself not innately problematic but it raises some challenges as the courses offered for the same degree are different at each centre.  For example\'2C one of the core courses offered at \'28PMB\'29 is \'E2\'80\'9CFoundations of Political Inquiry\'E2\'80\'9D which is compulsory but the same course is optional for students registered at \'28HC\'29. Indeed\'2C the course \'E2\'80\'9CResearch Methodology in a Political Context\'E2\'80\'9D is available for students at \'28HC\'29 and not \'28PMB\'29. Some of these courses might well cover the same subject area\'2C but it would be helpful if they are hamornised in terms of designation\'2C content etc. so that no room for doubt is left that students at both centres are receiving the same level of education and covering the same content as they are studying for the same degree.\line Again\'2C there is an imbalance in the course offerings in that at \'28PMB\'29 students are not given a choice in the core courses that they do\'2C except in one instance\'2C whereas the \'28HC\'29 students have a clear choice between two options at the core level.  This disadvantages students at \'28PMB\'29 to tie them down to courses and yet it gives flexibility to those who study at \'28HC\'29. One negative effect of this would be students preferring to register at \'28HC\'29 and being reluctant to register at \'28PMB\'29  creating all sorts of problems\'2C in terms of  increased teaching loads  of staff\'2C straining of facilities etc.\line With respect to Recognition of Prior Learning \'28Criterion 2\'29 the evaluator indicated that requirements should be made much more explicit for prospective students. They are vague in that they only indicate that a \'E2\'80\'9Cportfolio\'22 will be needed from the student for assessment to be admitted to the programme.\line The Directorate supports the recommendation that the programme should be provisionally accredited with conditions.\line \cell \pard 

